      · An analyst comparing the AI segment's Adjusted EBITDA to a peer that expenses restructuring costs within operating income would overstate relative performance.
      · Impairment add-backs are particularly dangerous for cross-period and cross-company comparisons because they can convert genuine value destruction into apparent profitability.
      · A peer company might not add back SBC, might treat restructuring differently, or might use a different depreciation methodology, making direct Adjusted EBITDA comparisons unreliable without normalizing for construction differences.
      · Because add-backs are not uniform across segments (D&A is concentrated in AI and Connectivity; SBC is concentrated in AI and Space; restructuring is exclusive to AI), the metric systematically reshapes the relative economics of each segment.
      · Any cross-segment or peer comparison using Segment Adjusted EBITDA must first normalize for: (i) capital intensity embedded in D&A, (ii) the real economic cost of equity compensation, (iii) the recurring nature of purportedly non-recurring charges, and (iv) the episodic but potentially massive impact of impairment write-downs.
